'''Domoic acid''' (DA), the neurotoxin that causes [[amnesic shellfish poisoning]] (ASP), is a [[kainic acid]] analog, [[heterocyclic]] [[amino acid]] associated with certain [[harmful algal bloom]]s.<ref name=FOCanada>{{ cite web | url = http://www2.glf.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/os/aes-sae/dapr-radp/index-e.php | title = Domoic Acid and ''Pseudo-nitzschia'' References | date = 2012-03-15 | publisher = Fisheries and Oceans Canada | accessdate = 2012-04-08 }}</ref>

==Occurrence==
In 1958, domoic acid was originally isolated from the [[red alga]] called "doumoi" or "hanayanagi" (''Chondria armata''<ref>{{ cite web | url = http://www.algaebase.org/search/species/detail/?species_id=3334 | title = ''Chondria armata'' (Kützing) Okamura | author = Guiry, M. D.; Guiry, G. M. | year = 2012 | work = AlgaeBase | publisher = National University of Ireland | accessdate = 2012-04-08 }}</ref>) in [[Japan]]. "Doumoi" is used as an [[anthelmintic]] in [[Tokunoshima, Kagoshima]].<ref>{{ cite book | editor = Botana, L. M. | author = Ramsdell, J. S. | chapter = The Molecular and Integrative Basis to Domoic Acid Toxicity | title = Phycotoxins: Chemistry and Biochemistry | publisher = Wiley-Blackwell | location = Cambridge, MA | year = 2007 | isbn = 0-8138-2700-0 | pages = 223–250 | doi = 10.1002/9780470277874.ch13 }}</ref> Domoic acid is also produced by some [[diatom]]s of the genus ''[[Pseudo-nitzschia]]''<ref name=FOCanada/> and by some strains of the diatom species ''Nitzschia navis-varingica''.<ref name=FOCanada/><ref>{{ cite web | url = http://www.marinespecies.org/hab/aphia.php?p=taxdetails&id=246595 | title = ''Nitzschia navis-varingica'' Lundholm & Moestrup, 2000 | work = HABs taxon details | publisher = Marine Species }}</ref>

''Pseudo-nitzschia multiseries'' loses most of its ability to produce domoic acid when it is cultured axenically. However, domoic acid production recovers when bacteria from the original culture are reintroduced to [[axenic]] cultures, indicating a bacterial association with domoic acid production in this species.<ref>{{ cite journal | author = Kobayashi, K.; Takata, Y.; Kodama, M. | title = Direct Contact between ''Pseudo-nitzschia multiseries'' and Bacteria is Necessary for the Diatom to Produce a High Level of Domoic Acid | journal = Fisheries Science | year = 2009 | volume = 75 | issue = 3 | pages = 771–776 | doi = 10.1007/s12562-009-0081-5 | url = http://www.springerlink.com/content/q31133564p04218n/fulltext.pdf | format = pdf }}</ref>  Other factors that affect the biosynthesis of domoic acid are reviewed by Bates and Trainer (2006),<ref>{{ cite book | author = Bates, S. S.; Trainer, V. L. | year = 2006 | chapter = The Ecology of Harmful Diatoms | editor = Granéli, E.; Turner, J.  | title = Ecology of Harmful Algae | series = Ecological Studies | volume = 189 | publisher = Springer-Verlag | location = Heidelberg | pages = 81–93 | isbn = 978-3-540-74009-4 | doi = 10.1007/978-3-540-32210-8_7 | url = http://www.springerlink.com/content/j388u727655u0v0w/fulltext.pdf | format = pdf }}</ref> Trainer et al. (2008),<ref>{{ cite book | author = Trainer, V. L.; Hickey, B. M.; Bates, S. S. | year = 2008 | chapter = Toxic Diatoms | editor = Walsh, P. J.; Smith, S. L.; Fleming, L. E.; Solo-Gabriele, H.; Gerwick, W. H. | title = Oceans and Human Health: Risks and Remedies from the Sea | publisher = Elsevier Science | location = New York | pages = 219–237 | isbn = 978-0-12-372584-4 }}</ref> Lelong et al. (2012)<ref name=lelong>{{ cite journal | author = Lelong, A.; Hégaret, H.; Soudant, P.; Bates, S. S. | year = 2012 | title = ''Pseudo-nitzschia'' (Bacillariophyceae) Species, Domoic Acid and Amnesic Shellfish Poisoning: Revisiting Previous Paradigms | journal = Phycologia | volume = 51 | issue = 2 | pages = 168–216 | doi = 10.2216/11-37.1 }}</ref> and Trainer et al. (2012).<ref>{{ cite journal | author = Trainer, V. L.; Bates, S. S.; Lundholm, N.; Thessen, A. E.; Cochlan, W. P.; Adams, N. G.; Trick, C. G. | year = 2012 | title = ''Pseudo-nitzschia'' Physiological Ecology, Phylogeny, Toxicity, Monitoring and Impacts on Ecosystem Health | journal = Harmful Algae | volume = 14 | pages = 271–300 | doi = 10.1016/j.hal.2011.10.025 }}</ref>

The increasing frequency and geographic extent of toxic algal blooms along populated coastlines is generally attributed to human activities.<ref>{{ cite journal | title = Toxic Diatoms and Domoic Acid in Natural and Iron Enriched Waters of the Oceanic Pacific | author = Silver, M. W.; Bargu, S.; Coale, S. L.; Benitez-Nelson, C. R.; Garcia, A. C.; Roberts, K. J.; Sekula-Wood, E.; Bruland, K. W.; Coale, K. H. | journal = PNAS | year = 2010 | volume = 107 | issue = 48 | pages = 20762–20767 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.1006968107 | url = http://www.pnas.org/content/107/48/20762.full.pdf | format = pdf }}</ref>

==Chemistry==
{{Expand section|date=June 2008}}
Domoic acid is a structural analog of [[kainic acid]] and [[proline]]. General aspects of domoic acid chemistry, including its isomers and degradation, are reviewed by Lelong et al. (2012).<ref name=lelong/>

==Toxicology==
Considerable recent research has been carried out by the [[Marine Mammal Center]] and other scientific centers on the association of domoic acid-producing [[harmful algal bloom]]s and [[neurological]] damage in [[marine mammal]]s of the [[Pacific Ocean]].

Domoic acid can [[bioaccumulation|bioaccumulate]] in [[ocean|marine]] organisms such as [[shellfish]], [[anchovy|anchovies]], and [[sardine]]s that feed on the [[phytoplankton]] known to produce this toxin.  DA can accumulate in high concentrations in the tissues of these plankton feeders when the toxic phytoplankton itself is high in concentration in the surrounding waters.

In [[mammal]]s, including [[human]]s, domoic acid acts as a [[neurotoxin]], causing [[short-term memory loss]], [[brain damage]] and, in severe cases, [[death]]. DA-producing [[algal bloom]]s are associated with the phenomenon of [[amnesic shellfish poisoning]] (ASP).  In marine mammals, domoic acid typically causes seizures and tremors.  In the brain, domoic acid especially damages the [[hippocampus]] and [[amygdaloid nucleus]]. It damages the [[neuron]]s by activating [[AMPA]] and [[kainate]] receptors, causing an influx of [[calcium]]. Although calcium flowing into cells is a normal event, the uncontrolled increase of calcium causes the cell to degenerate.  Because the hippocampus may be severely damaged, [[short-term memory loss]] occurs.

